1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:We investigate the class of single round, sealed bid auctions for a set of identical items to bidders who each desire one unit .
1-2:We adopt the worst case competitive framework defined by [9, 5] that compares the profit of an auction to that of an optimal single price sale of least two items .
1-3:In this paper, we first derive an optimal auction for three items, answering an open question from [8] .
1-4:Second, we show that the form of this auction is independent of the competitive framework used .
1-5:Third, we propose a schema for converting a given limited supply auction into an unlimited supply auction .
1-6:Applying this technique to our optimal auction for three items, we achieve an auction with a competitive ratio of 3.25, which improves upon the previously best known competitive ratio of 3.39 from [7] .
1-7:Finally, we generalize a result from [8] and extend our understanding of the nature of the optimal competitive auction by showing that the optimal competitive auction occasionally offers prices that are higher than all bid values .
1-8:F.2.2 [Analysis of Algorithms and Problem Complexity]: .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:The research area of optimal mechanism design looks at designing a mechanism to produce the most desirable outcome for the entity running the mechanism .
2-2:This problem is well studied for the auction design problem where the optimal mechanism is the one that brings the seller the most profit .
2-3:Here, the classical approach is to design such a mechanism given the prior distribution from which the bidders" preferences are drawn (See e.g., [12, 4]) .
2-4:Recently Goldberg et al .
2-5:[9] introduced the use of worst case competitive analysis (See e.g., [3]) to analyze the performance of auctions that have no knowledge of the prior distribution .
2-6:The goal of such work is to design an auction that achieves a large constant fraction of the profit attainable by an optimal mechanism that knows the prior distribution in advance .
2-7:Positive results in this direction are fueled by the observation that in auctions for a number of identical units, much of the distribution from which the bidders are drawn can be deduced on the fly by the auction as it is being run [9, 14, 2] .
2-8:The performance of an auction in such a worst case competitive analysis is measured by its competitive ratio, the ratio between a benchmark performance and the auction"s performance on the input distribution that maximizes this ratio .
2-9:The holy grail of the worstcase competitive analysis of auctions is the auction that achieves the optimal competitive ratio (as small as possible) .
2-10:Since [9] this search has led to improved understanding of the nature of the optimal auction, the techniques for on the fly pricing in these scenarios, and the competitive ratio of the optimal auction [5, 7, 8] .
2-11:In this paper we continue this line of research by improving in all of these directions .
2-12:Furthermore, we give evidence corroborating the conjecture that the form of the optimal auction is independent of the benchmark used in the auction"s competitive analysis .
2-13:This result further validates the use of competitive analysis in gauging auction performance .
2-14:We consider the single item, multi unit, unit demand auction problem .
2-15:In such an auction there are many units of a single item available for sale to bidders who each desire only one unit .
2-16:Each bidder has a valuation representing how much the item is worth to him .
2-17:The auction is performed by soliciting a sealed bid from each of the bidders and deciding on the allocation of units to bidders and the prices to be paid by the bidders .
2-18:The bidders are assumed to bid so as to maximize their personal utility, the difference between their valuation and the price they pay .
2-19:To handle the problem of designing and analyzing auctions where bidders may falsely declare their valuations to get a better deal, we will adopt the solution concept of truthful mechanism design (see, e.g., [9, 15, 13]) .
2-20:In a truthful auction, revealing one"s true valuation as one"s bid is an optimal strategy for each bidder regardless of the bids of the other bidders .
2-21:In this paper, we will restrict our attention to truthful (a.k.a., incentive compatible or strategyproof) auctions .
2-22:A particularly interesting special case of the auction problem is the unlimited supply case .
2-23:In this case the number of units for sale is at least the number of bidders in the auction .
2-24:This is natural for the sale of digital goods where there is negligible cost for duplicating 175 and distributing the good .
2-25:Pay per view television and downloadable audio files are examples of such goods .
2-26:The competitive framework introduced in [9] and further refined in [5] uses the profit of the optimal omniscient single priced mechanism that sells at least two units as the benchmark for competitive analysis .
2-27:The assumption that two or more units are sold is necessary because in the worst case it is impossible to obtain a constant fraction of the profit of the optimal mechanism when it sells only one unit [9] .
2-28:In this framework for competitive analysis, an auction is said to be β competitive if it achieves a profit that is within a factor of β ≥ 1 of the benchmark profit on every input .
2-29:The optimal auction is the one which is β competitive with the minimum value of β .
2-30:Previous to this work, the best known auction for the unlimited supply case had a competitive ratio of 3.39 [7] and the best lower bound known was 2.42 [8] .
2-31:For the limited supply case, auctions can achieve substantially better competitive ratios .
2-32:When there are only two units for sale, the optimal auction gives a competitive ratio of 2, which matches the lower bound for two units .
2-33:When there are three units for sale, the best previously known auction had a competitive ratio of 2.3, compared with a lower bound of 13 6 ≈ 2.17 [8] .
2-34:The results of this paper are as follows: • We give the auction for three units that is optimally competitive against the profit of the omniscient single priced mechanism that sells at least two units .
2-35:This auction achieves a competitive ratio of 13 6, matching the lower bound from [8] (Section 3) .
2-36:• We show that the form of the optimal auction is independent of the benchmark used in competitive analysis .
2-37:In doing so, we give an optimal three bidder auction for generalized benchmarks (Section 4) .
2-38:• We give a general technique for converting a limited supply auction into an unlimited supply auction where it is possible to use the competitive ratio of the limited supply auction to obtain a bound on the competitive ratio of the unlimited supply auction .
2-39:We refer to auctions derived from this framework as aggregation auctions (Section 5) .
2-40:• We improve on the best known competitive ratio by proving that the aggregation auction constructed from our optimal three unit auction is 3.25 competitive (Section 5.1) .
2-41:• Assuming that the conjecture that the optimal unit auction has a competitive ratio that matches the lower bound proved in [8], we show that this optimal auction for ≥ 3 on some inputs will occasionally offer prices that are higher than any bid in that input (Section 6) .
2-42:For the three unit case where we have shown that the lower bound of [8] is tight, this observation led to our construction of the optimal three unit auction. .
